===subject:Intervention
===from:Keith Bolton
===email:ssgsoja@hotmail.com
===date:Wed Apr 23 21:29:55 2003
===message:Intervention is a good thing when a country loses control over it's own citizens or militia groups threaten to take over the region. When there are brutal murders and mass killings. Stronger outside assistance is necessary to regain control. The invasion by Australia was done for the right reasons. Had they not stepped in, there would have been more killings, looting, etc. The main reason I agree with Australia invading East Timor is because Indonesia was in the process of becoming an independent nation by using legal voting procedures and the people were being killed for wanted to be free. Whether intervention should be local or global depends on the size of the threat. In this case, it should have been the UN with NATO backing them up with security forces and supervision. This backing has to be ongoing to prevent or discourage any uprisings in the future. There has to be a deterent from violence at all times. That is why we have the United States of America. It makes the bad guys think twice about doing the wrong thing.
